Object reference
- Emp emp = new Emp();
  - emp variable is referred to as an Object reference
  emp = new Emp();

  String s1 = "Java";
  s1 = "Oracle";

Class reference
- Class c = Emp.class;
- Class c = String.class;
- Class c = Class.forName("com.citiustech.model.Emp");
- Object obj = c.newInstance();

Method reference
- Function<String,Integer> f = Integer::parseInt;
- ToIntFunction<String> f = Integer::parseInt;

Types of Functions in java.util.function package
- Function, BiFunction, ToIntFunction, ... (some input, some output)
- Supplier (some return value, no input parameters)
- Consumer, BiConsumer, ... (no return value/void, some input parameter)
- UnaryOperator, BinaryOperator, ... (input and output of the same type)
- Predicate (some input, output will be a boolean always)


Collection API
--------------
List
- duplicate elements
- indexed/ordered collection (elements can be accessed randomly by it's position)

Set
- unique elements
- may be unordered (elements cannot be accessed by it's position)

Map
- pair (key, value)
  - key unique, value can be duplicate


Stream API
----------
- A brand new API for data processing in Java
- Stream is just a wrapper on the source from where the data will be fed

methods of the Stream API are classified into 3 types:
creation
- stream(), of(), iterate(), generate(), empty(), ..

intermediate
- filter(), map(), flatMap(), distinct(), sorted(), peek(), limit(), skip()

terminal
- forEach(), toArray(), collect(), reduce(), min(), max(), count(), sum(), anyMatch(), ..


map, reduce and filter
- map -> transformation
- reduce -> aggregation
- filter -> condition/restriction



